Note:
==============================================================================
oklab - Oklab and Oklch Perceptual Color Spaces (Bjorn Ottosson 2020)
==============================================================================

Oklab is a perceptually-uniform colour space published by Bjorn Ottosson
in 2020 (https://bottosson.github.io/posts/oklab/) designed to improve
on CIELAB at modern display gamuts. The forward pipeline:

    1. linear-RGB -> LMS via the matrix M1:

           |  0.4122214708  0.5363325363  0.0514459929 |
       M1 = |  0.2119034982  0.6806995451  0.1073969566 |
           |  0.0883024619  0.2817188376  0.6299787005 |

    2. LMS -> LMS' via cube-root per component (LMS'_i = cbrt(LMS_i)).

    3. LMS' -> Lab via the matrix M2:

           |  0.2104542553   0.7936177850  -0.0040720468 |
       M2 = |  1.9779984951  -2.4285922050   0.4505937099 |
           |  0.0259040371   0.7827717662  -0.8086757660 |

Oklch is the polar form (L, C, h) of Oklab. Euclidean distance in Oklab
is a perceptually meaningful colour-difference metric (oklab_delta_e
below).

References:
  - B. Ottosson, "A perceptual color space for image processing", 2020
  - https://bottosson.github.io/posts/oklab/
==============================================================================
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Arith
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STRUCT TYPE DEFINITIONS
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "ColorOklab":
    l as Float
    a as Float
    b as Float
End Type

Type called "ColorOklch":
    l as Float
    c as Float
    h as Float
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NUMERIC HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "sqrtf" takes x as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Square-root via arithmetic_core.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Delegates to Arith.sqrt.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~14 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return Arith.sqrt(x)
End Process

Process called "cbrtf" takes x as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Real cube root with sign preservation. Used three times per
    oklab encoding.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Scale-reduce |x| into [1, 8] via division/multiplication by 8.0,
    eight Newton iterations on y^3 - x = 0, then reassemble with
    pow(2) scaling.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~ 80 FLOPs per call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure, bounded loop.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let sign be 1.0
    Let m be x
    If x is less than 0.0:
        Set sign to 0.0 minus 1.0
        Set m to 0.0 minus x
    End If
    If m is less than 0.000000000000000000000000000000001:
        Return 0.0
    End If
    Let scale_up be 0
    Let scratch be m
    While scratch is greater than 8.0:
        Set scratch to scratch divided by 8.0
        Set scale_up to scale_up plus 1
        If scale_up is greater than 400:
            Set scratch to 8.0
        End If
    End While
    Let scale_dn be 0
    While scratch is less than 1.0:
        Set scratch to scratch multiplied by 8.0
        Set scale_dn to scale_dn plus 1
        If scale_dn is greater than 400:
            Set scratch to 1.0
        End If
    End While
    Let y be scratch
    Let iter be 0
    While iter is less than 10:
        Let y2 be y multiplied by y
        Let num be (y2 multiplied by y) minus scratch
        Let den be 3.0 multiplied by y2
        If den is less than or equal to 0.0:
            Set iter to 10
        Otherwise:
            Set y to y minus (num divided by den)
            Set iter to iter plus 1
        End If
    End While
    Let pow2 be 1.0
    Let iu be 0
    While iu is less than scale_up:
        Set pow2 to pow2 multiplied by 2.0
        Set iu to iu plus 1
    End While
    Let pow2_dn be 1.0
    Let id be 0
    While id is less than scale_dn:
        Set pow2_dn to pow2_dn multiplied by 2.0
        Set id to id plus 1
    End While
    Set y to (y multiplied by pow2) divided by pow2_dn
    Return sign multiplied by y
End Process

Process called "pow_real" takes base as Float, exponent as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Real exponentiation x^y via exp(y * ln(x)). Used by the sRGB transfer
    function during the rgb->oklab pipeline. Honours the IEEE-754 / POSIX
    convention that x^0 = 1 for all finite x including zero.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Mercator series for ln, Maclaurin for exp; range-reduction by
    halving / doubling. The exponent==0 short-circuit is checked before
    the log-domain reduction so that pow_real(0.0, 0.0) returns 1.0
    instead of falling through to the non-positive-base early-return.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~ 70 FLOPs per call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If exponent is equal to 0.0:
        Return 1.0
    End If
    If base is less than or equal to 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    End If
    Let m be base
    Let k be 0
    While m is greater than or equal to 2.0:
        Set m to m divided by 2.0
        Set k to k plus 1
        If k is greater than 2048:
            Return 0.0
        End If
    End While
    Let kd be 0
    While m is less than 1.0:
        Set m to m multiplied by 2.0
        Set kd to kd plus 1
        If kd is greater than 2048:
            Return 0.0
        End If
    End While
    Let z be (m minus 1.0) divided by (m plus 1.0)
    Let z2 be z multiplied by z
    Let term be z
    Let ln_m be 0.0
    Let idx be 0
    While idx is less than 30:
        Let denom be Arith.int_to_float((2 multiplied by idx) plus 1)
        Set ln_m to ln_m plus (term divided by denom)
        Set term to term multiplied by z2
        Set idx to idx plus 1
    End While
    Set ln_m to ln_m multiplied by 2.0
    Let ln2 be 0.69314718055994530941723212145817656807550013436025525412
    Let ln_base be ln_m plus (Arith.int_to_float(k) multiplied by ln2)
    Set ln_base to ln_base minus (Arith.int_to_float(kd) multiplied by ln2)
    Let y be exponent multiplied by ln_base
    Let n_floor be Arith.float_to_int(y divided by ln2)
    If y is less than 0.0:
        If Arith.int_to_float(n_floor) is greater than (y divided by ln2):
            Set n_floor to n_floor minus 1
        End If
    End If
    Let r_y be y minus (Arith.int_to_float(n_floor) multiplied by ln2)
    Let exp_r be 1.0
    Let s_term be 1.0
    Let i be 1
    While i is less than 32:
        Set s_term to (s_term multiplied by r_y) divided by Arith.int_to_float(i)
        Set exp_r to exp_r plus s_term
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Let two_n be 1.0
    If n_floor is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let nn be n_floor
        While nn is greater than 0:
            Set two_n to two_n multiplied by 2.0
            Set nn to nn minus 1
        End While
    Otherwise:
        Let nn be 0 minus n_floor
        While nn is greater than 0:
            Set two_n to two_n divided by 2.0
            Set nn to nn minus 1
        End While
    End If
    Return exp_r multiplied by two_n
End Process

Process called "sin_deg" takes deg as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Sine in degrees for oklch_to_oklab conversion and hue rotation.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Reduce to [-180, 180], convert to radians, sum the Taylor series.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~ 30 multiplies per call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let d be deg
    While d is greater than or equal to 360.0:
        Set d to d minus 360.0
    End While
    While d is less than 0.0:
        Set d to d plus 360.0
    End While
    Let pi_const be 3.14159265358979323846
    Let x be (d multiplied by pi_const) divided by 180.0
    If x is greater than pi_const:
        Set x to x minus (2.0 multiplied by pi_const)
    End If
    Let result be 0.0
    Let term be x
    Let sign be 1.0
    Let n be 1
    While n is less than 28:
        Set result to result plus (sign multiplied by term)
        Set term to (term multiplied by x) multiplied by x
        Let denom1 be Arith.int_to_float((2 multiplied by n) plus 1)
        Let denom2 be Arith.int_to_float(2 multiplied by n)
        Set term to term divided by denom1
        Set term to term divided by denom2
        Set sign to 0.0 minus sign
        Set n to n plus 1
    End While
    Return result
End Process

Process called "cos_deg" takes deg as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Cosine in degrees via sin(90 - x).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Calls sin_deg(90 - deg).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Same as sin_deg.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return sin_deg(90.0 minus deg)
End Process

Process called "atan2_deg" takes y as Float, x as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Two-argument arctangent in degrees, range [0, 360).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Maclaurin series with octant dispatch.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~ 50 FLOPs per call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let pi_const be 3.14159265358979323846
    If x is equal to 0.0:
        If y is greater than 0.0:
            Return 90.0
        End If
        If y is less than 0.0:
            Return 270.0
        End If
        Return 0.0
    End If
    Let abs_y be Arith.absf(y)
    Let abs_x be Arith.absf(x)
    Let t be abs_y divided by abs_x
    Let inverted be 0
    If t is greater than 1.0:
        Set t to 1.0 divided by t
        Set inverted to 1
    End If
    Let result be 0.0
    Let term be t
    Let sign be 1.0
    Let n be 0
    Let t2 be t multiplied by t
    While n is less than 60:
        Let denom be Arith.int_to_float((2 multiplied by n) plus 1)
        Set result to result plus ((sign multiplied by term) divided by denom)
        Set term to term multiplied by t2
        Set sign to 0.0 minus sign
        Set n to n plus 1
    End While
    If inverted is equal to 1:
        Set result to (pi_const divided by 2.0) minus result
    End If
    If x is less than 0.0:
        If y is greater than or equal to 0.0:
            Set result to pi_const minus result
        Otherwise:
            Set result to (0.0 minus pi_const) plus result
        End If
    Otherwise:
        If y is less than 0.0:
            Set result to 0.0 minus result
        End If
    End If
    Let deg_val be (result multiplied by 180.0) divided by pi_const
    While deg_val is less than 0.0:
        Set deg_val to deg_val plus 360.0
    End While
    While deg_val is greater than or equal to 360.0:
        Set deg_val to deg_val minus 360.0
    End While
    Return deg_val
End Process

Process called "srgb_to_linear_local" takes c as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Local sRGB inverse transfer for the rgb_to_oklab pipeline.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Piecewise: c/12.92 for c<=0.04045 else ((c+0.055)/1.055)^2.4.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Toe branch is two FP ops; gamma dominated by pow_real.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let sign be 1.0
    Let a be c
    If c is less than 0.0:
        Set sign to 0.0 minus 1.0
        Set a to 0.0 minus c
    End If
    Let result be 0.0
    If a is less than or equal to 0.04045:
        Set result to a divided by 12.92
    Otherwise:
        Let inside be (a plus 0.055) divided by 1.055
        Set result to pow_real(inside, 2.4)
    End If
    Return sign multiplied by result
End Process

Process called "linear_to_srgb_local" takes c as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Forward sRGB transfer for the oklab_to_rgb pipeline.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Piecewise.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Toe branch two FP ops; gamma dominated by pow_real.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let sign be 1.0
    Let a be c
    If c is less than 0.0:
        Set sign to 0.0 minus 1.0
        Set a to 0.0 minus c
    End If
    Let result be 0.0
    If a is less than or equal to 0.0031308:
        Set result to a multiplied by 12.92
    Otherwise:
        Let inv_gamma be 1.0 divided by 2.4
        Set result to (1.055 multiplied by pow_real(a, inv_gamma)) minus 0.055
    End If
    Return sign multiplied by result
End Process

Process called "clamp01_local" takes v as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Unit clamp for output channels.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Two compares.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If v is less than 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    End If
    If v is greater than 1.0:
        Return 1.0
    End If
    Return v
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LINEAR-RGB <-> OKLAB
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "linear_rgb_to_oklab" takes r as Float, g as Float, b as Float returns ColorOklab:
    @Reasoning
    Apply the M1 matrix to linear RGB, take the cube root of each LMS
    component, then apply the M2 matrix to yield Oklab L, a, b. Constants
    are from Ottosson's 2020 paper.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Two 3x3 matrix multiplies straddling three cbrt calls.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Dominated by the three cbrt evaluations.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let l_lms be (((0.4122214708 multiplied by r) plus (0.5363325363 multiplied by g)) plus (0.0514459929 multiplied by b))
    Let m_lms be (((0.2119034982 multiplied by r) plus (0.6806995451 multiplied by g)) plus (0.1073969566 multiplied by b))
    Let s_lms be (((0.0883024619 multiplied by r) plus (0.2817188376 multiplied by g)) plus (0.6299787005 multiplied by b))
    Let l_p be cbrtf(l_lms)
    Let m_p be cbrtf(m_lms)
    Let s_p be cbrtf(s_lms)
    Let out be a value of type ColorOklab
    Set out.l to (((0.2104542553 multiplied by l_p) plus (0.7936177850 multiplied by m_p)) plus ((0.0 minus 0.0040720468) multiplied by s_p))
    Set out.a to (((1.9779984951 multiplied by l_p) plus ((0.0 minus 2.4285922050) multiplied by m_p)) plus (0.4505937099 multiplied by s_p))
    Set out.b to (((0.0259040371 multiplied by l_p) plus (0.7827717662 multiplied by m_p)) plus ((0.0 minus 0.8086757660) multiplied by s_p))
    Return out
End Process

Process called "oklab_to_linear_rgb" takes lab as ColorOklab, out_rgb as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Invert the M2 matrix to yield LMS', cube each component to recover
    LMS, then invert the M1 matrix to yield linear RGB. Outputs four
    floats (r, g, b, 1.0) at offsets 0, 8, 16, 24 of out_rgb.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Two 3x3 matrix multiplies (inverse of M1 and M2). The inverse
    coefficients are from Ottosson's paper.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three multiplies + nine multiplies per matrix; cube reverse is three
    multiplies.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller guarantees out_rgb has at least 32 writable bytes.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let l_p be lab.l plus ((0.3963377774 multiplied by lab.a) plus (0.2158037573 multiplied by lab.b))
    Let m_p be lab.l minus ((0.1055613458 multiplied by lab.a) plus (0.0638541728 multiplied by lab.b))
    Let s_p be lab.l minus ((0.0894841775 multiplied by lab.a) plus (1.2914855480 multiplied by lab.b))
    Let l_lms be (l_p multiplied by l_p) multiplied by l_p
    Let m_lms be (m_p multiplied by m_p) multiplied by m_p
    Let s_lms be (s_p multiplied by s_p) multiplied by s_p
    Let r be ((4.0767416621 multiplied by l_lms) plus ((0.0 minus 3.3077115913) multiplied by m_lms)) plus (0.2309699292 multiplied by s_lms)
    Let g be (((0.0 minus 1.2684380046) multiplied by l_lms) plus (2.6097574011 multiplied by m_lms)) plus ((0.0 minus 0.3413193965) multiplied by s_lms)
    Let b be (((0.0 minus 0.0041960863) multiplied by l_lms) plus ((0.0 minus 0.7034186147) multiplied by m_lms)) plus (1.7076147010 multiplied by s_lms)
    Let _wr be store_float_at_oklab(out_rgb, 0, r)
    Let _wg be store_float_at_oklab(out_rgb, 8, g)
    Let _wb be store_float_at_oklab(out_rgb, 16, b)
    Let _wa be store_float_at_oklab(out_rgb, 24, 1.0)
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: OKLAB <-> OKLCH
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "oklab_to_oklch" takes lab as ColorOklab returns ColorOklch:
    @Reasoning
    Polar conversion: C = sqrt(a^2 + b^2), h = atan2(b, a) in degrees.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    sqrtf + atan2_deg.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One sqrt + one atan2.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type ColorOklch
    Set out.l to lab.l
    Set out.c to sqrtf((lab.a multiplied by lab.a) plus (lab.b multiplied by lab.b))
    Set out.h to atan2_deg(lab.b, lab.a)
    Return out
End Process

Process called "oklch_to_oklab" takes lch as ColorOklch returns ColorOklab:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse polar conversion: a = C cos(h), b = C sin(h) (h in degrees).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    cos_deg + sin_deg.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One sin + one cos.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type ColorOklab
    Set out.l to lch.l
    Set out.a to lch.c multiplied by cos_deg(lch.h)
    Set out.b to lch.c multiplied by sin_deg(lch.h)
    Return out
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FULL sRGB <-> OKLAB PIPELINES
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "rgb_to_oklab" takes r as Float, g as Float, b as Float returns ColorOklab:
    @Reasoning
    Full sRGB (non-linear) to Oklab pipeline. Linearises each channel
    via the IEC 61966-2-1 inverse transfer then dispatches to
    linear_rgb_to_oklab.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Three sRGB inverse transfers + linear_rgb_to_oklab.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three pow_real + three cbrt = dominant cost.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let r_lin be srgb_to_linear_local(r)
    Let g_lin be srgb_to_linear_local(g)
    Let b_lin be srgb_to_linear_local(b)
    Return linear_rgb_to_oklab(r_lin, g_lin, b_lin)
End Process

Process called "oklab_to_rgb" takes lab as ColorOklab, out_rgb as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Full Oklab to sRGB pipeline. Dispatches to oklab_to_linear_rgb into
    a 32-byte scratch buffer (heap-allocated), applies the sRGB forward
    transfer to each channel, then writes the result back at offsets
    0/8/16/24. The scratch is leaked here so callers that hold the
    pointer can inspect it; the recommended path is to pass a single
    out_rgb buffer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Reads linear values via bits_to_float_local from the scratch and
    encodes them via linear_to_srgb_local.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three sRGB encodings dominate.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns out_rgb (32 bytes).
    @End Security_Scope
    Let l_p be lab.l plus ((0.3963377774 multiplied by lab.a) plus (0.2158037573 multiplied by lab.b))
    Let m_p be lab.l minus ((0.1055613458 multiplied by lab.a) plus (0.0638541728 multiplied by lab.b))
    Let s_p be lab.l minus ((0.0894841775 multiplied by lab.a) plus (1.2914855480 multiplied by lab.b))
    Let l_lms be (l_p multiplied by l_p) multiplied by l_p
    Let m_lms be (m_p multiplied by m_p) multiplied by m_p
    Let s_lms be (s_p multiplied by s_p) multiplied by s_p
    Let r_lin be ((4.0767416621 multiplied by l_lms) plus ((0.0 minus 3.3077115913) multiplied by m_lms)) plus (0.2309699292 multiplied by s_lms)
    Let g_lin be (((0.0 minus 1.2684380046) multiplied by l_lms) plus (2.6097574011 multiplied by m_lms)) plus ((0.0 minus 0.3413193965) multiplied by s_lms)
    Let b_lin be (((0.0 minus 0.0041960863) multiplied by l_lms) plus ((0.0 minus 0.7034186147) multiplied by m_lms)) plus (1.7076147010 multiplied by s_lms)
    Let r_srgb be linear_to_srgb_local(r_lin)
    Let g_srgb be linear_to_srgb_local(g_lin)
    Let b_srgb be linear_to_srgb_local(b_lin)
    Let _wr be store_float_at_oklab(out_rgb, 0, clamp01_local(r_srgb))
    Let _wg be store_float_at_oklab(out_rgb, 8, clamp01_local(g_srgb))
    Let _wb be store_float_at_oklab(out_rgb, 16, clamp01_local(b_srgb))
    Let _wa be store_float_at_oklab(out_rgb, 24, 1.0)
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PERCEPTUAL DELTA-E
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "oklab_delta_e" takes c1 as ColorOklab, c2 as ColorOklab returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Oklab is designed so Euclidean distance is a perceptually meaningful
    colour-difference. No weighting is required.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    sqrt((dL)^2 + (da)^2 + (db)^2).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three multiplies + two adds + sqrt.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let dl be c1.l minus c2.l
    Let da be c1.a minus c2.a
    Let db be c1.b minus c2.b
    Let sum be ((dl multiplied by dl) plus (da multiplied by da)) plus (db multiplied by db)
    Return sqrtf(sum)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: OKLCH MANIPULATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "oklch_rotate_hue" takes lch as ColorOklch, degrees as Float returns ColorOklch:
    @Reasoning
    Rotate hue by a signed number of degrees, with wrap-around to
    [0, 360).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Modular addition.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single add + bounded modulus loop.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type ColorOklch
    Set out.l to lch.l
    Set out.c to lch.c
    Let h_new be lch.h plus degrees
    While h_new is greater than or equal to 360.0:
        Set h_new to h_new minus 360.0
    End While
    While h_new is less than 0.0:
        Set h_new to h_new plus 360.0
    End While
    Set out.h to h_new
    Return out
End Process

Process called "oklch_lighten" takes lch as ColorOklch, amount as Float returns ColorOklch:
    @Reasoning
    Additively increase L*, leaving chroma and hue unchanged.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    L' = L + amount. Oklab L is unbounded above formally; for sRGB
    content produced by rgb_to_oklab and any downstream display pipeline
    the lightness lies in [0, 1].
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single add.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type ColorOklch
    Set out.l to lch.l plus amount
    Set out.c to lch.c
    Set out.h to lch.h
    Return out
End Process

Process called "oklch_chroma_clip" takes lch as ColorOklch returns ColorOklch:
    @Reasoning
    Reduce chroma until the resulting colour lies inside the sRGB gamut.
    Uses bisection on chroma in [0, original-C] guided by an
    in-gamut test of the resulting Oklab -> linear RGB output.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Convert oklch -> oklab -> linear RGB; if any channel is outside
    [0, 1] then halve chroma and retry, up to 30 iterations. Final
    result is the highest chroma found that produced an in-gamut colour.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Up to 30 oklab_to_linear_rgb conversions; each is ~ 30 FLOPs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure, bounded.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type ColorOklch
    Set out.l to lch.l
    Set out.h to lch.h
    Let low_c be 0.0
    Let high_c be lch.c
    Let iter be 0
    While iter is less than 30:
        Let mid_c be (low_c plus high_c) divided by 2.0
        Let trial be a value of type ColorOklch
        Set trial.l to lch.l
        Set trial.c to mid_c
        Set trial.h to lch.h
        Let trial_lab be oklch_to_oklab(trial)
        Let l_p be trial_lab.l plus ((0.3963377774 multiplied by trial_lab.a) plus (0.2158037573 multiplied by trial_lab.b))
        Let m_p be trial_lab.l minus ((0.1055613458 multiplied by trial_lab.a) plus (0.0638541728 multiplied by trial_lab.b))
        Let s_p be trial_lab.l minus ((0.0894841775 multiplied by trial_lab.a) plus (1.2914855480 multiplied by trial_lab.b))
        Let l_lms be (l_p multiplied by l_p) multiplied by l_p
        Let m_lms be (m_p multiplied by m_p) multiplied by m_p
        Let s_lms be (s_p multiplied by s_p) multiplied by s_p
        Let r_lin be ((4.0767416621 multiplied by l_lms) plus ((0.0 minus 3.3077115913) multiplied by m_lms)) plus (0.2309699292 multiplied by s_lms)
        Let g_lin be (((0.0 minus 1.2684380046) multiplied by l_lms) plus (2.6097574011 multiplied by m_lms)) plus ((0.0 minus 0.3413193965) multiplied by s_lms)
        Let b_lin be (((0.0 minus 0.0041960863) multiplied by l_lms) plus ((0.0 minus 0.7034186147) multiplied by m_lms)) plus (1.7076147010 multiplied by s_lms)
        Let in_gamut be 1
        If r_lin is less than 0.0:
            Set in_gamut to 0
        End If
        If r_lin is greater than 1.0:
            Set in_gamut to 0
        End If
        If g_lin is less than 0.0:
            Set in_gamut to 0
        End If
        If g_lin is greater than 1.0:
            Set in_gamut to 0
        End If
        If b_lin is less than 0.0:
            Set in_gamut to 0
        End If
        If b_lin is greater than 1.0:
            Set in_gamut to 0
        End If
        If in_gamut is equal to 1:
            Set low_c to mid_c
        Otherwise:
            Set high_c to mid_c
        End If
        Set iter to iter plus 1
    End While
    Set out.c to low_c
    Return out
End Process

